This example represents a simple binary tree where a recursive function counts the nodes at a given depth. The code is presented in the style of a teaching shell, where function arguments and function return values are explicitly shown. This format makes the recursive calls visually apparent.
```rust
fn countNodes(x: Option<Box<Node>>, level: u32) -> u32 {
    // Start of the recursive function
    match x {
        Some(node) => {
            // Calculate the distance from the current node to the top level
            let distance = level + 1;

            // Base case: if we are at the root level, return 1.
            // Recursive case: call the function for each child.
            println!("Evaluating node at depth {}", distance);
            return 1 + match (node.left.clone(), node.right.clone()) {
                (Some(a), Some(b)) => countNodes(Some(a), distance) + countNodes(Some(b), distance),
                (Some(a), None) => countNodes(Some(a), distance),
                (None, Some(b)) => countNodes(Some(b), distance),
                _ => 1,  // Base case
            };
        }
        None => 1,
    };
}
```
The take-home lesson here is how to write a recursive function by focusing on the base case, the recursive case, and the signal for termination. The function takes in a node and a level number and returns the total number of nodes at that depth. Every call to the function explicitly shows the recursive process, with each node branching into left and right children. This visual structure makes the recursive pattern clear.
